	 which is better?
		implementing Runnable is superior to extending Thread for three reasons:
		1. Multiple Inheritance: Java allows a class to extend only one other class. If you extend Thread, your class cannot inherit from any other base class.
		2. Separation of Concerns: Runnable represents the task to be performed(what to do), while Thread is the worker that executes it(how to run it).
			Decoupling them makes your code cleaner and more modular.
		3. Thread Pooling: Modern apps rarely create threads manually by extending thread class. Instead, they use ExecutorService. These services are designed to work 
			with Runnable tasks, not Thread subclasses.

	Virtual Threads (Project Loom).
		Before Java 21, every Java thread was a "Platform Thread" (a 1:1 wrapper around an expensive OS thread). If you created 10,000 threads, your system would crash.
		With Virtual Threads, you can create millions of threads because they are managed by the JVM, not the OS.
		Best for I/O-bound tasks: (Database calls, API requests, Kafka consuming)

		For simple tasks, Runnable is better than extending Thread because it preserves the inheritance hierarchy. However, for a production microservice, 
		I prefer using ExecutorService with Virtual Threads (in Java 21). This allows us to handle massive I/O concurrency without the overhead of context-switching
		between expensive OS platform threads.
		

