	1. "Fixed Thread Pool" : This is the most common implementation. It limits the number of concurrent threads, preventing your application from crashing 
		under high load (e.g., a burst of Kafka messages).

	When using ExecutorService, you must consider:
		Thread Pool Sizing: If a task is CPU-bound, set the pool size to the number of available cores. If it's I/O-bound (DB calls, Kafka), you can set it much higher.
		Graceful Shutdown: Applications that don't call .shutdown() can leave "zombie" threads running, preventing the JVM from exiting or causing memory leaks.

