39. What is singleTon desing pattern
	The Singleton pattern is a creational design pattern that ensures a class has only one instance in the entire application and provides a global point of access to
	that instance. It’s commonly used for things like logging, configuration settings, cache managers, or thread pools
example: Thread-Safe Double-Checked Locking - To make singleton class thread safe, we use three key components:
	volatile keyword: Ensures that the change to instance is immediately visible to all threads and prevents "instruction reordering" by the compiler.
	Synchronized block: Only allows one thread to create the object at a time.
	Double-check: We check null twice—once outside the lock (for performance) and once inside (for safety).

public class SafeSingleton {
    private static volatile SafeSingleton instance;					// 1. volatile is mandatory for thread safety here

    private SafeSingleton() {
        System.out.println("Singleton Instance Created by: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }

    public static SafeSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {							        // First check (No locking, fast)
            synchronized (SafeSingleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {							// Second check (Inside lock, safe)
                    instance = new SafeSingleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}



Execution with 2 Threads
Here is the step-by-step execution logic showing how the threads interact:

public class SingletonTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating Thread 1
        Thread thread1 = new Thread(() -> {
            SafeSingleton s1 = SafeSingleton.getInstance();
            System.out.println("Thread 1 got: " + s1.hashCode());
        }, "Thread-1");

        // Creating Thread 2
        Thread thread2 = new Thread(() -> {
            SafeSingleton s2 = SafeSingleton.getInstance();
            System.out.println("Thread 2 got: " + s2.hashCode());
        }, "Thread-2");

        thread1.start();
        thread2.start();
    }
}

The Step-by-Step Flow:
T1 and T2 start: Both call getInstance().
First Check: Both see instance == null.
Synchronization: T1 reaches the synchronized block first and enters. T2 is blocked and waits.
Second Check (T1): T1 confirms instance is still null and creates the object.
Release: T1 exits the block. The volatile keyword ensures the new value of instance is flushed to main memory.
Entry (T2): T2 now enters the synchronized block.
Second Check (T2): T2 checks instance == null. Because T1 just updated it, the check returns false.
Exit: T2 exits without creating a new object and returns the one created by T1.

40. The Bean Lifecycle
   1. Bean Definition: ​Spring reads your configuration (XML, Java Config, or Annotations). It creates a BeanDefinition.
   2. Instantiation: Spring calls the constructor to create the object. The object exists, but dependencies aren’t injected yet.
   3. Dependency Injection: Spring performs Dependency Injection (e.g., injecting the UserRepository into your UserService).
   4. Aware Interfaces: If the bean implements interfaces like BeanNameAware, Spring gives it its metadata.
   5. Initialization: Spring calls methods annotated with @PostConstruct or any custom init() method.
   6. Ready for Use: The bean is now available for your application logic.
   7. Destruction: When the container shuts down, Spring calls methods annotated with @PreDestroy to clean up resources (like closing database connections).

The Complete Spring Bean Lifecycle
​1. Bean Definition Loading: ​Spring reads your configuration (XML, Java Config, or Annotations). It creates a BeanDefinition.
​2. Instantiation: ​Spring instantiates the bean using the bean's constructor. 
​3. Dependency Injection: ​Spring injects the dependencies using setter injection or field injection (@Autowired). 
​4. Aware Interfaces: ​Spring checks if the bean implements any Aware interfaces. This allows the bean to "talk back" to the Spring container.
	​BeanNameAware: Gives the bean its ID/Name.
	​BeanFactoryAware: Gives the bean access to the factory that created it.
	​ApplicationContextAware: Gives the bean access to the entire Spring context.
​5. BeanPostProcessor: Before Initialization - ​Spring passes the bean through the postProcessBeforeInitialization method of any registered BeanPostProcessor.
	​Role: spring handles annotations like @PostConstruct.
​6. Initialization: ​Now the bean is configured, and Spring performs the actual initialization:
	​@PostConstruct: The modern standard for init logic.
	​Custom init-method: Defined in @Bean(initMethod = "...").
​7. BeanPostProcessor: After Initialization - ​The bean passes through postProcessAfterInitialization.
	​Critical Fact: Spring AOP Proxies are created. If your bean uses @Transactional, Spring replaces your original bean with a "proxy" bean here to handle the
	database transactions.
​8. Ready for Use: ​The bean is fully baked and live in the ApplicationContext. It stays here until the application is stopped or the scope (like request/session) expires.
​9. Destruction: ​When the container shuts down (e.g., context.close()), the bean is cleaned up:
	​@PreDestroy: The standard for cleanup logic.
	​destroy(): Part of the DisposableBean interface.
	​Custom destroy-method: Defined in @Bean(destroyMethod = "...").

41.  Explain why constructor injection is preferred
    In Spring Boot, Constructor Injection is the gold standard for dependency injection, especially when building robust, production-grade applications. 
    While @Autowired on a field is shorter to write, constructor injection offers structural advantages that field injection simply can't match.
      1. Requirement of Final Fields (Immutability)
          . constructor injection allows you to declare your dependencies as final.
          •	Field Injection: You cannot use final because the field must be modified by Spring via reflection after the object is instantiated.
          •	Constructor Injection: The dependency is assigned at the moment of creation. This ensures the dependency cannot be changed (mutated) or become null during 
                                    the lifecycle of the bean.

          example: private final ProductService productService; // 'final' is only possible with constructor injection

      2. Ease of Unit Testing
          . This is perhaps the biggest practical advantage. When you use constructor injection, your class has no "hidden" dependencies.
          •	No Spring Needed: You can instantiate the class in a plain JUnit test using the new keyword and pass in a Mockito mock.
          •	With Field Injection: You are forced to use @SpringBootTest (which is slow) or use reflection utilities to "force" the dependency into the private field.
      
      3. Prevention of NullPointerExceptions
 			Constructor injection guarantees that a bean is never created in an uninitialized state. If a required dependency is missing, the application will fail to compile
    		or fail immediately at startup rather than throwing a NullPointerException at runtime when a specific method is called.

	4. Circular Dependency Detection
		Spring can detect circular dependencies (Class A needs Class B, and Class B needs Class A) much more effectively with constructor injection. It will throw a
    	BeanCurrentlyInCreationException at startup, forcing you to fix a flawed architectural design early.

	Pro-Tip: Use Lombok to save space
	 you can use the @RequiredArgsConstructor annotation from Lombok. It will automatically generate the constructor for all final fields, keeping your code clean while
	 maintaining all the benefits of constructor injection.

